62,"updated_at":"2021-08-23T12:48:22.967Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":4,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":412,"readers_count":411,"score":87.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":395682,"topic_slug":"a-question-about-field-oriented","display_username":"Daniel Wenbo","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":29982,"username":"UnofficialForth","name":"UnofficialForth","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/unofficialforth/{size}/167902_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":48748,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/a-question-about-field-oriented/395682/6","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":2967190,"name":"Daniel Wenbo","username":"mendax1234","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/mendax1234/{size}/156242_2.png","created_at":"2021-09-03T12:13:23.504Z","cooked":"<p>Hello , l have checked my navx, it works well.  But in a swerve drive , l can’t rotate the robot and drive it at the same time .  Now , our robot only has two swerve modules .  Does it have any effect with the field oriented?</p>","post_number":7,"post_type":1,"posts_count":62,"updated_at":"2021-09-03T12:13:23.504Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":4,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":386,"readers_count":385,"score":92.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":395682,"topic_slug":"a-question-about-field-oriented","display_username":"Daniel Wenbo","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":29982,"username":"UnofficialForth","name":"UnofficialForth","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/unofficialforth/{size}/167902_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":48748,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/a-question-about-field-oriented/395682/7","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":2967193,"name":"UnofficialForth","username":"UnofficialForth","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/unofficialforth/{size}/167902_2.png","created_at":"2021-09-03T12:52:22.065Z","cooked":"<p>Are the two diagonal from each other or on the same side of the robot?</p>","post_number":8,"post_type":1,"posts_count":62,"updated_at":"2021-09-03T12:52:22.065Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":7,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":3,"reads":379,"readers_count":378,"score":95.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":395682,"topic_slug":"a-question-about-field-oriented","display_username":"UnofficialForth","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":48748,"username":"mendax1234","name":"Daniel Wenbo","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/mendax1234/{size}/156242_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":29982,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"FRC Team 4272  Mentor | World's FLL Emcee"},"post_url":"/t/a-question-about-field-oriented/395682/8","custom_user_title":"FRC Team 4272  Mentor | World's FLL Emcee","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":2967195,"name":"Allen Nuttle","username":"nuttle","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/nuttle/{size}/124105_2.png","created_at":"2021-09-03T13:15:06.889Z","cooked":"<p>A useful way to think about field-oriented drive is that it’s just using the orientation of the robot, relative to the field, to modify the operator controls.  Typically, there are three inputs from these controls: X-translation, Y-translation, and rotation about the center of the robot.  You are basically just using math to do the same thing as if the operator control was always being turned so it faces the same way as the robot.</p>
<p>The WPILib stuff hides the math, but this is just a transformation of the X and Y values – the rotation is unchanged.  The math here is going from Cartesian coordinates (X, Y) to Polar ones (r, θ), adding some value (from the gyro) to the angle, and then converting back to Cartesian.  (See <a href="https://www.mathsisfun.com/polar-cartesian-coordinates.html.)">https://www.mathsisfun.com/polar-cartesian-coordinates.html.)</a></p>
<p>So the number of wheels doesn’t enter into things here.  In the code, functions such as hypot(), atan2(), sin(), and cos() are used to perform this math (trigonometry).</p>","post_number":9,"post_type":1,"posts_count":62,"updated_at":"2021-09-03T13:19:20.923Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":5,"reads":378,"readers_count":377,"score":150.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":395682,"topic_slug":"a-question-about-field-oriented","display_username":"Allen Nuttle","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.mathsisfun.com/polar-cartesian-coordinates.html.)","internal":false,"reflection":false,"clicks":5}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":3}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":14283,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/a-question-about-field-oriented/395682/9","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":3}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":3,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":2967196,"name":"Allen Nuttle","username":"nuttle","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/nuttle/{size}/124105_2.png","created_at":"2021-09-03T13:30:31.237Z","cooked":"<p>One thing that can happen with swerve when translating and rotating is that the speeds wind up maxed out, this can sometimes interfere with rotation while translating.  In WPILib, normalizeWheelSpeeds() is one way to manage this.  (See <a href="https://gi